<article id="post-2196" class="post-2196 post type-post status-publish format-standard hentry category-children category-family category-general tag-babies tag-dearmonkey tag-sibling-rivalry">
	<header class="entry-header">
		
		<h2 class="entry-title"><a href="http://geoff.wp/2009/10/brother-or-sister/" rel="bookmark">Brother or sister?</a></h2>	</header><!-- .entry-header -->

	
	
	<div class="entry-content">
		<p>Well, Monkey, today we&#8217;d hoped to find out whether or not your sibling-to-be will be a boy or a girl. At this point, we don&#8217;t know if you&#8217;ll have a little sister or a little brother. All we do know is that whatever the sex of your younger sibling is, they&#8217;re healthy and moving.<br />
In fact, they&#8217;re so healthy and moving that they made it difficult to get a good view of them on the ultrasound. The doctor/ultrasound operator couldn&#8217;t see &#8220;boy&#8221; or &#8220;girl&#8221; because the baby kept moving so much.<br />
Moving around constantly and being difficult? Yep, that sounds like a Sowrey, alright&#8230;<br />
 <a href="http://geoff.wp/2009/10/brother-or-sister/#more-2196" class="more-link">Continue reading<span class="screen-reader-text"> &#8220;Brother or sister?&#8221;</span></a></p>
	</div><!-- .entry-content -->

