<article id="post-1478" class="post-1478 post type-post status-publish format-standard hentry category-general category-technology tag-domains tag-hosting tag-how-to tag-internet tag-websites">
	<header class="entry-header">
		
		<h2 class="entry-title"><a href="http://geoff.wp/2009/08/how-to-host-your-own-website-the-simple-version/" rel="bookmark">How to host your own website (the simple version)</a></h2>	</header><!-- .entry-header -->

	
	
	<div class="entry-content">
		<p>I&#8217;ve been around this internet thing for a long time, and I&#8217;ve set up probably far more than my share of websites (both for myself and my clients). After a while, setting up websites becomes largely a by-rote-memory thing and you don&#8217;t have to put a lot of effort into it.<br />
But that belittles the reality: it&#8217;s not really that easy to set up a website if you have no idea how it&#8217;s done. And let&#8217;s be honest, here, I&#8217;m not talking about MySpace. I&#8217;m talking about using your own domain name (e.g. mytotallyawesomewebsite.com)   as a way of branding yourself, your message, and hopefully standing out from the crowd.<br />
One thing I can assure you, though: it&#8217;s also not that hard. Really.<br />
