<article id="post-1471" class="post-1471 post type-post status-publish format-standard hentry category-general tag-canada tag-canadian tag-immigration">
	<header class="entry-header">
		
		<h2 class="entry-title"><a href="http://geoff.wp/2009/07/canadian-citizenship-questions-are-kinda-funny/" rel="bookmark">Canadian citizenship questions are kinda funny</a></h2>	</header><!-- .entry-header -->

	
	
	<div class="entry-content">
		<p>My friend Julia is getting ready to have her Canadian Citizenship test, as she&#8217;s tired of being merely a Permanent Resident, and now apparently wants to have more say in these taxes she&#8217;s been paying.<br />
To that end, she&#8217;s received and is now reviewing the requisite materials for the test. (I offer you <a href="http://docs.google.com/Doc?docid=0AdMNaHmNLgy9ZGRwYnBocTNfMzBjN3pmdmJjYw&amp;hl=en">the list of questions she gave to me</a>, unaltered, as a starting point.) As one might expect, the test has a number of questions that, yes, an average born-and-raised-in-Canada Canadian would flunk. (I would imagine the same is true of most countries.) Some of these are taken for granted, as just about everyone just accepts things as they are.<br />
But some of these questions are &#8230; well, let&#8217;s say that they just scream for alternative answers.<br />
 <a href="http://geoff.wp/2009/07/canadian-citizenship-questions-are-kinda-funny/#more-1471" class="more-link">Continue reading<span class="screen-reader-text"> &#8220;Canadian citizenship questions are kinda funny&#8221;</span></a></p>
	</div><!-- .entry-content -->

